==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shend
<hw>Shend</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shent</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>scendan</ets> to
disgrace, bring to shame, from <ets>sceand</ets>, <ets>sceond</ets>,
disgrace, dishonor, shame; akin to G. <ets>schande</ets>, Goth.
<ets>skanda</ets>. See <er>Shame</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To injure, mar, spoil, or harm.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Loss of time <xex>shendeth</xex> us.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fear my body will be <qex>shent</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To blame, reproach, or revile; to degrade, disgrace,
or put to shame.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>R.
Browning.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The famous name of knighthood foully <qex>shend</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She passed the rest as Cynthia doth <qex>shend</qex>⟦br⟧
The lesser stars.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shendful</ent>⟦br⟧
